div3.p:
 --Recorder James K. Caskie, an urbane and courteous gentleman, presided yesterday as the controlling head of the above popular but not much appreciated institution.

Applicants to the bar of justice were not kept waiting hours for a thimble full of law that could have been doled out at a glance, but all suitors received their quietus in a rapid yet reasonable way. Consuming no unnecessary time in fumbling over the musty tomes of antiquated legal lore to fortify his judgment, this gentleman by the facility with which he comprehends a legal point and cuts Gordian knots, entitles himself to the thanks of every newspaper reporter.

